In a #medium pot{}, bring @water{5%cups} to a boil, then reduce to a low simmer. (For 4 servings, use a #large pot{} and @water{8%cups}.) (You'll use the simmering water in Step 5.)

Wash and dry produce.

Trim and quarter @zucchini{1%unit} lengthwise; cut crosswise into ½-inch-thick pieces.

Remove @Italian pork sausage mix{9%ounces} from casing if necessary; discard casing. Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{a drizzle} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add sausage and cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and almost cooked through, ~{2-4%minutes}.

Add zucchini; cook, stirring constantly, until zucchini is tender and sausage is cooked through, ~{2-4%minutes} more.

Turn off heat; using a #slotted spoon{}, transfer sausage and zucchini to a #paper-towel-lined plate{}. Reserve pan.

Meanwhile, in a #small bowl{}, whisk together @sun-dried tomato paste{1%ounce}, @hot water{1%tbsp}, and a pinch of @salt{pinch}.

> You can use hot water from the tap or the simmering water from Step 1.

Heat @cooking oil{a drizzle} in pan used for sausage over medium heat. Add @Arborio rice{3/4%cup} and cook, stirring frequently, until translucent, ~{1-2%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Add @chicken stock concentrate{2%units} and 1 cup simmering water to pan with rice. Cook, stirring, until liquid has mostly absorbed.

Repeat with remaining simmering water—adding ½ cup at a time and stirring until liquid has absorbed—until rice is al dente and mixture is creamy, ~{25-30%minutes}.

> Depending on the size of your pan, you may need a little more or a little less liquid.

Reduce heat to medium low. Stir in @cream sauce base{4%ounces} and half the @Parmesan cheese{3%tablespoons}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until risotto thickens and cream sauce is incorporated, ~{2-4%minutes}.

Remove risotto from heat and stir in sausage and zucchini. Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if desired.

Divide risotto between #shallow bowls{}. Dollop with sun-dried tomato topping and sprinkle with remaining Parmesan. Serve.

> Pork Sausage is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.